               <t:note>
                  <t:date type="foundation" notBefore="1400" notAfter="1500">1400-1500</t:date>
                  <t:desc type="foundation">Local tradition tells that the church was built in the Aksumite time, under <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS3729ellaAm">King ʿAlāmedā</t:persName>, but re-established by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4327GabraMa">Gabra Masqal</t:persName>.</t:desc>
                  <t:ab type="history">Dabr. An intact old structure (possibly the old church) stands in the compound, in front of the recent church. 
Aksumite pillars are used in the recent church building. 
Some old wooden parts are preserved in the treasury.
A burial place, possibly old, can be seen behind the church.  
</t:ab>
                  <t:ab type="tabot">
                     <t:measure quantity="22"/>Tābots (22): those remembered are <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS6819Mary">Mary</t:persName>, <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS3249Cyriacus">Qirqos</t:persName>, 
                     <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS1906Ananyao">ʾAnānyā</t:persName>, <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS7049Michael">Michael</t:persName>, 
                     <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9162TaklaHa">Takla Haymanot</t:persName>, 2 of <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10581Zamika">ʾAragāwi</t:persName>,
                     <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS12016Evangelists#Four">Four Living Creatures</t:persName>, 
                     <t:persName type="tabot" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4306GabraMa">Gabra Manfas Qǝddus</t:persName>, <t:ref type="authFile" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/TrueCross">Holy Cross</t:ref>.</t:ab>
                  <t:ab type="description">
                     <t:figure>
                        <t:graphic url="Sites/WQ.tif">
                           <t:desc>The church photographed by Denis Nosnitsin during the Ethio-SPaRe project.</t:desc>
                        </t:graphic>
                     </t:figure>8 Mss. photographed: <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq001">WQ-001</t:ref> “The Rite of the Holy Week”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq002">WQ-002</t:ref> “Homily on the Sabbath of Christians”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq003">WQ-003</t:ref> “Book of the Funeral Rite”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq004">WQ-004</t:ref> “Story of St. Mary”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq005">WQ-005</t:ref> “Missal”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq006">WQ-006</t:ref> “Vita of Cyriacus”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq007">WQ-007</t:ref> “Four Gospels”; <t:ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESwq008">WQ-008</t:ref> “Miracles of Jesus”.</t:ab>
  
